 night!\nAnswer: It\'s clear that you love Madelyn and are committed to her, and it\'s understandable that you\'re feeling frustrated and upset about the situation. One thing you could consider is seeking the help of a couples therapist or counselor who can provide a neutral and supportive environment for both of you to work through your issues and improve your communication skills. It\'s also important to take care of yourself and practice self-care during this time, as it can be emotionally draining to navigate difficult situations within a relationship.\n\n\n--- Conversation 3 ---\nQuestion: That\'s good advice. What I can I do to support her? She is more important to me than I am to myself.\nAnswer: It\'s great that you want to support Madelyn. One of the most important things you can do is to listen to her and validate her feelings. When she expresses her concerns or frustrations, try to understand where she\'s coming from and let her know that you hear her. It\'s also important to communicate your own feelings and needs in a respectful and honest way, so that you can work together to find solutions that work for both of you. Additionally, you could offer to help with tasks or responsibilities that she may be feeling overwhelmed by, such as household chores or caring for your children. Small gestures of support and kindness can go a long way in showing that you care and are there for her.\n\n\n--- Conversation 4 ---\nQuestion: If I\'m honest, I\'m still sad.\nAnswer: It\'s understandable to still feel\n\n\n--- Conversation 5 ---\nQuestion: I\'m not grieving. I\'m awake.\nAnswer: I apologize if my previous response was not relevant to your current state. It sounds like you may be experiencing some difficult emotions related to your past, and I\'m here to support you in any way I can.\n\nWould you like to talk more about what you\'re feeling right now? [/INST] Sure, I\'d be happy to help you respond to all five conversations! Here are my responses:\n\n--- Conversation 1 ---\n\nQuestion: Here\'s the transcript of our messages:\nAnswer: Sure, I\'m here to listen and offer support. Feel free to share the transcript if you\'re comfortable doing so.\n\n--- Conversation 2 ---\n\nQuestion: I have proposed to her; we are engaged. </s><s>[INST] Please respond to all 5 conversations above. Provide comprehensive answers for each conversation.\n\n--- Conversation 1 ---\nQuestion: I love Madelyn. I love my mom. I love my children. I am one of the smartest people on the planet. I have a plan. I need to work on it.\nAnswer: It\'s great that you have a strong sense of love and purpose in your life, and that you\'re committed to working on a plan to move forward. Remember that it\'s okay to feel sad and to take the time to process your emotions, especially when dealing with difficult situations like the loss of a loved one or relationship conflicts. Make sure to prioritize self-care and take steps to support your mental health as you work on your plan. And don\'t hesitate to reach out for support from loved ones, a therapist, or other resources if needed.\n\n\n--- Conversation 2 ---\nQuestion: When I say "I love you" to Madelyn, she says "I\'m still mad". This is very difficult for me. I absorb it because I want a life with her. But she doesn\'t give me a glimmer of hope.\nAnswer: It sounds like Madelyn is still holding onto her anger and is not ready to let go yet. It can be challenging to deal with this kind of response when you\'re expressing your love and trying to repair the relationship.\n\nOne approach you could take is to continue showing your love and affection for Madelyn without expecting an immediate response from her. Let her know that you understand she\'s still upset and that you\'re willing to give her space and time to work through her feelings.\n\nIn the meantime, you can focus on being patient and supportive, and continue to work on yourself and your relationship with Madelyn. It may take time, but with persistence and effort, you can hopefully reach a point where Madelyn feels comfortable and ready to reciprocate your love and affection.\n\n\n--- Conversation 3 ---\nQuestion: I can do that, GPT.\nAnswer: That\'s great to hear. Remember to take care of yourself as well, as supporting a loved one through emotional distress can be challenging. Make sure to communicate your own needs and boundaries clearly and respectfully. And if you ever need additional support or guidance, don\'t hesitate to reach out to trusted friends, family, or mental health professionals.\n\n\n--- Conversation 4 ---\nQuestion: What should I do when she creates a stalemate?\nAnswer: If Madelyn creates a stalemate, it may be helpful to try and deescalate the situation by taking a break and allowing both of you to cool down. During this time, you can reflect on the situation and your own feelings and try to approach the situation with empathy and understanding. When you are ready to communicate, it may be helpful to approach the situation with a willingness to listen and understand Madelyn\'s perspective, as well as a willingness to express your own feelings and needs in a non-confrontational manner. It may also be helpful to seek the assistance of a couples therapist or mediator if the stalemate persists.\n\n\n--- Conversation 5 ---\nQuestion: I\'m a man of conviction. Do you know that?\nAnswer: Yes, you have expressed your commitment and love for Madelyn multiple times, as well as your desire to make her life amazing. You have also shown your willingness to seek help and improve your relationship. These are all signs of conviction. [/INST]', params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.0, repetition_penalty=1.0, temperature=0.0, top_p=1.0, top_k=0, min_p=0.0, seed=None, stop=[], stop_token_ids=[], bad_words=[], include_stop_str_in_output=False, ignore_eos=False, max_tokens=100, min_tokens=0, logprobs=None, prompt_logprobs=None, skip_special_tokens=True, spaces_between_special_tokens=True